AGI - On 7 October 2023 he marked a watershed in the relations between Israel and the Holy See >: after the massacre of Hamas and the start of the war in Gaza, "the relationship has become more tense and problematic". It is the memory of Raphael Schutz, > Israeli ambassador to the Holy See from 2021 to August 2024. In an interview with AGI, the diplomat speaks of the first two years of his term as "normal, calm, positive". But the terrorist attack and the subsequent conflict in the Strip, with their loads of death and suffering, modified the scenario.&nbsp;
Pope Francis in this year and a half has always expressed strong closeness to the drama of the Palestinians of Gaza, especially children, central in his calls for peace and prayers. As well as great attention has always given the tragedy of the hostages in the hands of Hamas and Islamic Jihad, meeting their families and also a group of former kidnapped.
But other elements of the conflict, "like the goal of Hamas, the fact that Israel has been attacked also from the north and Iran, the suffering of the Israelis in the south of the country and in the kibbutz and communities around the Strip have not been mentioned either by the Pope or by the Vatican," emphasizes the retired ambassador.&nbsp;To this has been added a use of the words deemed improper from Israel >, "as an ambassador &nbsp;
Francis adds, "he mentioned the right to self-defense of Israel two or three times, while instead of the suffering of Gaza he spoke one hundred times, once a week, sometimes even more, a proportion that for us is prevented and unjust".&nbsp;That's what, Schutz is convinced that the silence of the Israeli government at the death of the pontiff was not correct. Recognizing Herzog's warm message and Israeli ambassadors in the world who signed condolence books, the ambassador emphasised the "formal conduct": "All differences of opinion must be discussed and dialogue is the way to do so. But when a leader dies, the code of conduct should be respected."
Other ambassadors made themselves heard about X, first of all from Rome Jonathan Peled, who praised "a compassionate leader who incessantly promoted dialogue, peace and justice", but also the representative in Bulgaria, Yosi Levi Sfari. In his message of condolences from Sofia he stressed that, "though not all the words of Pope Francis have always had echo in us, we must recognize and value his consolidated commitment in the fight against anti-Semitism and in the promotion of interreligious dialogue". Levi Sfari has made "honour for his unique and compassionate personality, relaunching the "his shortened appeal for peace and liberation of all hostages".

