AGI - The office of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu> expressed his condolences for the death of Pope Francis, three days later, his death. "The State of Israel expresses its most felt condolences to the Catholic Church and the Catholic community around the world for the disappearance of Pope Francis. May he rest in peace," he wrote the office on social media.
So far only the Israeli President Isaac Herzog had known the death of the pontiff in his country. The Ministry of Foreign Affairs published a condolence message for Francis' disappearance, but the message was subsequently deleted.&nbsp; In statements released on Wednesday, ministry sources minimized the deletion of the message and said that "every day" is published by mistake of the tweets that are then deleted. "It is not significant," the sources said about the message, which was reproduced by several press bodies and published by an account linked to the ministry.
<div </div
It says: "Replace in peace, Pope Francis. May your memory be a blessing", along with an image of the pontiff at the Western Wall of Jerusalem. The same sources reported that Israel will be represented at the funeral of the Pope on Saturday by his ambassador to the Holy See, Yaron Sideman, and stressed the difficulty of mobilizing the Israeli authorities since the ceremony falls on Shabbat>, the day of Jewish rest. Pope Francis was a fervent supporter of peace in the world and almost daily asked the end of the Israeli offensive in Gaza, even asking that he be investigated as possible genocide.&nbsp;
